Druids are more martial than mages, roughly on par with
clerics, though their religious restrictions mean they
are often less effective in combat than clerics.  A
druid forswears wearing most metals, preferring to
make use of natural materials such as wood or leather.
Many silver and gold objects are also allowed to them,
because of these metals' association with the moon and
sun.  However, heavy armors such as platemail are
forbidden to them.  A druid may use some shields --
small shields of wooden or leather construction,
primarily.

Druids have significantly more leeway with weapons.
A druid may use most daggers, sickles, staves, spears,
and other polearms, in addition to most missile
weapons, even if these contain metallic components.  In
addition, the druid may use hammers and other blunt
weapons permitted to clerics, so long as those weapons
are not metallic.

Druids follow a wide range of philosophies, and
may be good or evil, lawful or chaotic, as they
please.  However, a druid must maintain a certain
personal balance in order to retain his powers; a
druid who goes too far to any one extreme will find
himself unable to call upon nature.

A druid's primary characteristics are wisdom and
charisma.  Wisdom is necessary to understand the
mysteries of Gaea, and charisma aids in establishing
the necessary sense of empathy with Nature.
